unjust dispossession of an Indigenous population. This groundbreaking book explores two forms of critical geography: first, archipelagos of empire, examining how the Vietnam War is linked to the US military buildup in Guam and unwavering support of Israel, and second, corresponding archipelagos of trans-Indigenous resistance, tracing how Chamorro decolonization efforts and Palestinian liberation struggles are connected through the Vietnamese refugee figure. Considering distinct yet overlapping modalities of refugee and Indigenous displacement, Gandhi offers tools for imagining emergent forms of decolonial solidarity between refugee settlers and Indigenous peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aRefugeeszGuamxHistoryy20th century. 0aRefugeeszGuamy20th century. 0aRefugeeszIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aRefugeeszIsraely20th century. 0aSettler colonialismxPolitical aspects. 0aVietnamesezGuamxHistoryy20th century. 0aVietnamesezGuamy20th century. 0aVietnamesezIsraelxHistoryy20th century. 0aVietnamesezIsraely20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520976832zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520976832zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520976832/original  a978-3-11-076649-3 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA  aZDB-23-UCY